{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1340"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1340"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.2,0.36,0.28,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1340"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104922"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1340"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-12-01T18:03:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T17:43:56+09:30","updatedAction":"revised","acceptedAt":"2025-06-05T17:40:45+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 09:03:28"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1340"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"2888"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87308"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38031"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87308"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104922"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man undergoes surgical correction of adhesive small bowel obstruction, which has been attributed to adhesions from an appendicectomy in his youth. The patient has type 2 diabetes and no other comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFive days after the procedure, the patient is making satisfactory progress. However, it is noted that his serum sodium has been below the normal range for the past two days. It is currently 132 mEq/L (137 - 145).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be determined next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Morning cortisol","Serum glucose","Serum osmolality","Urine osmolality","Urine sodium"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHyponatraemia has a diverse range of aetiologies and, if not identified, treated and reversed, can lead to permanent and serious complications for the patient. In the workup of hyponatraemia, one of the first steps is to determine the patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum glucose\u003C/strong\u003E for hyperglycaemia. As the patient is diabetic and has recently had surgery, it would not be unusual for his serum glucose to be high, causing an osmotic water shift from the intracellular to extracellular space and a resultant dilutional hyponatraemia. High levels of lipids and proteins may also cause a similar \u0022pseudohyponatraemia\u0022.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum osmolality\u003C/strong\u003E,\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eurine osmolality\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0and\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eurine sodium\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0are all appropriate tests to determine the aetiology of a patient\u0027s hyponatraemia; however, it is first important to check for hyperglycaemia and calculate the corrected sodium. These three tests, when interpreted together, can help differentiate between hypovolemic, euvolemic, and hypervolemic hyponatremias. They may also provide insight into whether the hyponatraemia is due to anti-diuretic hormone dysregulation such as in SIADH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorning cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E levels may help identify specific etiologies of hyponatraemia, including primary adrenal insufficiency. However, measuring morning cortisol would usually only be considered once a true hyponatraemia is confirmed and findings suggest a hypovolaemic hyponatraemia with high urine sodium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperglycaemia is an important potential cause of pseudohyponatraemia."],"references":["Verbalis J, Goldsmith S, Greenberg A, Korzelius C, Schrier R, Sterns R et al. Diagnosis, Evaluation, and Treatment of Hyponatremia: Expert Panel Recommendations. The American Journal of Medicine. 2013;126(10):S1-S42. Available from: https://www.amjmed.com/article/S0002-9343(13)00605-0/fulltext","Lam Q, Wijeratne N. Comparison of commonly used equations for sodium adjustment in hyperglycaemia. Pathology. 2025 Feb 1;57(1):113\u20136. Available from: https://www.pathologyjournal.rcpa.edu.au/article/S0031-3025(24)00242-3/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87308"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1340"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87308"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T17:43:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T17:44:33+09:30","number":9,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-06-05T17:44:06+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-1340-9.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T231447Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=882f120c840bd6d4b15ed0b41dbe889aebc5e0f1274de9e6ac598f0c70f906ae"},"rela